Yes the pay and lack of parental support makes teaching a challenge but I enjoy it a lot.

(That's not to say that I have no respect for the job, I've been teaching at university for 7 years and I know well enough that teachers are absolute heroes! I wouldn't be able to teach high school for sure!)

I studied mechanical engineering 3.5 years and loved it but wanted to be a teacher. I didn't like the idea of having a degree in education as I felt I would be pigeon-holed into that career. I changed my major to Applied Math and was able to get hired by a private school that doesn't require a teaching certification.
I'm working through a non university but state recognized organization to achieve a teaching certification.
I may go back to university for a masters degree but I'm not certain what I would want.

Ah, I see, in Belgium that's actually sufficient to be allowed to teach math. If you have any math credits in university, you're qualified to teach high school. Shortage of teachers, they need the "lateral entrants" as they call it here.
They promote that people follow these educational tracks, but it only makes a difference in pay afaik, not in being allowed.
Pro-tip: have you thought about statistical data-analysis

If you like applied math, that's a field that is really interesting, has a massive shortage of good profiles and can really use people with a background both in and outside math to be able to understand both the technical and practical aspects

I think the public school system would allow me to still teach since we also have a shortage. I've seen them give exceptions to people that have degrees related to the HS classes they would teach. Ex) Literature/Journalism for a middle school grammar classes or writing classes.

I have considered the professional world of math. I'm not sure what I would want to do. I don't have a strong statistics background or I would at least need to study before trying to interview for a job. 


I have considered getting a Six Sigma certification as that has a strong cross over to the engineering world. A had a few internships in manufacturing and have a background in sustainability. I like the premise of trying to maximize productivity without completely destroying the planet.

For math teachers especially I imagine, there's a shortage of those about everywhere in the world!
I have heard of Six Sigma, but it seems to be a specific American qualification. We had several people in the clan with a Six Sigma but I never truly figured out what it was other than an extracurricular certification on the crossroads between math and engineering.

Research in productivity is an interesting field. I haven't done it myself and only briefly encountered it in my own master, but it really struck me how much work could still be done there from an analytical / statistical point of view.

Especially as you say, combining it with sustainability. The single "highest yield" endpoint is obviously outdated, and alternative ways of measuring product yield should definitely be looked into and tested, be it in manufacturing or agriculture, that take into account other mid-term and long-term costs such as environmental cost, resource consumption and potentially diminished availability of resources, and risks of overexploitation and overproduction vs. scarcity (which drives up the price and creates demand)
It's a very complex matter and when I learned about it (more than 15 years ago), models were all extreme simplifications and based on highest yield, I truly hope there has been an evolution since.

(And I say highest yield, but in practice, it's of course "highest profit margin" that people really want to optimize, with highest yield just a proxy for that, and ignoring that production yield and price may be negatively correlated - i.e., the supply & demand curve.)

I don't see how unless Fizzer makes an algorithmic function for the map making software. They are hard because you have to manually select each territory for each bonus. So on a straightforward map, you're just selecting 4 territories, click a button, now those 4 territories are assigned to that one bonus value. With INSS, you have to make exponentially more bonuses. Now on top of that initial 4 territory bonus, you have to make 4 more bonuses for the 4 possibilities of only controlling one territory within that bonus. Then 8 more for each possibility of controlling two territories, and so on. Then you have to test run it multiple times with a fine tooth comb to make sure you didn't make any mistakes in your 500+ confusing bonuses.
If AI could do it (which it could) it will come eventually
